meta {
  name: 07 Verify Registration Access
  type: http
  seq: 7
}

get {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/users/manage/me/permissions?branchId={{branchId}}
  body: none
  auth: bearer
}

params:query {
  branchId: {{branchId}}
}

auth:bearer {
  token: {{businessAccessToken}}
}

tests {
  // This is the EXACT endpoint kaltros-fe calls to decide which module tabs/routes
  // to show. The FE reveals a module when it is BOTH enabled for the branch
  // (`branchModules`) AND permission-allowed (`modules[].moduleAllowed`). We assert
  // Registration satisfies both â€” i.e. the new user will see it in kaltros-fe.
  test("200 OK", function () {
    expect(res.getStatus()).to.equal(200);
  });
  test("registration is ENABLED for the branch (branchModules)", function () {
    const mods = (res.getBody().data.branchModules || []).map(function (m) { return m.moduleKey; });
    expect(mods, "branchModules should include 'registration'").to.include("registration");
  });
  test("registration is PERMISSION-ALLOWED (moduleAllowed)", function () {
    const allowedModules = (res.getBody().data.modules || [])
      .filter(function (m) { return m.moduleAllowed; })
      .map(function (m) { return m.moduleKey; });
    expect(allowedModules, "modules[] should include an allowed 'registration' group").to.include("registration");
  });
  test("has the registration:view capability", function () {
    expect(res.getBody().data.allowed || [], "allowed[] should include 'registration:view'").to.include("registration:view");
  });
}

docs {
  Step 7 â€” **verify the new user can access the Registration module in
  kaltros-fe**, run **as the new user** (token swapped in step 6). This calls the
  *exact* endpoint the front-end uses to build its module tab bar and gate its
  routes: `GET /users/manage/me/permissions?branchId=â€¦`.

  ## How kaltros-fe decides module visibility

  In `PermissionsProvider.tsx` a module's tab **and** route are shown only when it
  is **both**:

  1. **enabled for the branch** â€” present in the response's `branchModules`
     (driven by Branchâ†’Module enablement, step 3), **AND**
  2. **permission-allowed** â€” present in `modules[]` with `moduleAllowed: true`
     (i.e. the user has at least one allowed permission in it â€” from the role
     baseline and/or the explicit grant in step 5).

  `ModuleGuard` applies the same check to the `/registration` route, so a module
  that fails either half is hidden **and** its route redirects to the user's first
  allowed module.

  This request asserts Registration passes both halves (`branchModules` includes
  `registration`, `modules[]` has an allowed `registration` group, and `allowed[]`
  includes `registration:view`). If all three pass, logging into kaltros-fe as this
  user shows the **Registration** tab and lets them open `/registration`.

  ## If the `moduleAllowed` / `registration:view` assertions FAIL

  `registration` must be a **permission-bearing** module for the FE to ever reveal
  it â€” an enablement-only module (no permission keys) can never be `moduleAllowed`.
  This was fixed in the backend (`system-modules.constant.ts` â€” `registration` +
  `lab_operations` are permission-bearing; `ROLE_DEFAULT_MODULES` grants
  `registration` to `receptionist`). **Restart the backend** so the change loads.

  ## If only the `branchModules` assertion fails

  The branch hasn't enabled `registration` â€” re-run step 3 (Enable Branch Modules)
  for this branch.
}
